
                     HEDIT v1.0 Technical Reference
                   CP/M 2.2 Hex Editor for the IMSAI 8080
                   =======================================


    1. PROJECT OVERVIEW

    HEDIT is a full-screen hex editor written in Intel 8080 assembly
    language for CP/M 2.2.  It uses a gap buffer data structure for
    efficient insertion and deletion, VT100/ANSI escape sequences for
    screen rendering, and supports both raw binary and Intel HEX file
    formats.

    Target platform:  IMSAI 8080 with CP/M 2.2
    CPU:              Intel 8080 (no Z80 instructions)
    Terminal:         VT100/ANSI compatible, 80x24
    Assembler:        Microsoft M80 (Macro-80)
    Linker:           Microsoft L80


    2. SOURCE FILES

    The project consists of 11 assembly modules, one include file,
    and a preprocessing script.

    Source Modules (link order):
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    File          Purpose                    Key Exports
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    HEDIT.MAC     Entry point, main loop,    INSMODE, DIRTY, DRTLINE,
                  action dispatch            CURBDP, TPATOP, DOEXIT,
                                             EDITMODE, NIBBLE

    HEXSCR.MAC    Terminal I/O, screen       SCRINIT, SCRDRAW, SCREDCL,
                  rendering, info bar,       INFOBAR, CURPOS, STATMSG,
                  cursor positioning         OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO,
                                             OUTN4HX, OUTN2HX, ISLOAD

    HEXKEY.MAC    Key input, VT100 ESC       GETKEY, KBDTBL, CSITBL,
                  sequence decoder           SS3TBL, CTKTBL, CTQTBL

    HEXGAP.MAC    Gap buffer engine          GBINIT, GBINSRT, GBDLFT,
                  (byte-level operations)    GBDELRT, GBMVLT, GBMVRT,
                                             GBMVTP, GBMVEND, GBMVTO,
                                             GBRDBLK, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND,
                                             GBCSOFF, GBGAPBG, GBGAPEN

    HEXIO.MAC     File load/save, Intel      FIOPEN, FISAVE, FIPROMPT,
                  HEX parser/writer          FISAVFN, FISMOD, WRKFCB

    HEXMENU.MAC   ESC menu overlay           MNUSHOW

    HEXSRCH.MAC   Hex and ASCII search       SRFIND, SRFNDNX

    HEXBLK.MAC    Block mark, copy,          BLMARK, BLCOPY, BLDEL,
                  delete, paste              BLPASTE

    HEXKBND.MAC   Key binding init from      KBINIT
                  HEDIT.KEY config file

    HEXVIRT.MAC   Virtual buffer I/O         VIMODE, VISAVALL, VIGOTO
                  for large files

    HEXHELP.MAC   Help screen overlay        HLPSHOW, BMDATEND
    ---------------------------------------------------------------

    IMPORTANT: HEXHELP.MAC must be linked LAST because BMDATEND marks
    the end of all static code and data.  The gap buffer is allocated
    from BMDATEND to the top of TPA.

    Other Files:
      HEDIT.INC    Shared equates (included by all .MAC files)
      CPMFMT.PY    Python preprocessor (inlines includes, normalizes
                   CR+LF line endings, appends Ctrl-Z EOF marker)
      CLAUDE.md    Project rules and conventions


    3. BUILD PROCESS

    Step 1: Preprocess all source files

      python CPMFMT.PY

    This inlines HEDIT.INC into each .MAC file, normalizes line
    endings to CR+LF, and appends a Ctrl-Z EOF marker.  This is
    required because M80 terminates input on Ctrl-Z in included
    files.

    To preprocess specific files only:

      python CPMFMT.PY HEDIT.MAC HEXSCR.MAC

    Step 2: Assemble each module

      M80 =HEDIT
      M80 =HEXSCR
      M80 =HEXKEY
      M80 =HEXGAP
      M80 =HEXIO
      M80 =HEXMENU
      M80 =HEXSRCH
      M80 =HEXBLK
      M80 =HEXKBND
      M80 =HEXVIRT
      M80 =HEXHELP

    Each produces a .REL relocatable object file.

    Step 3: Link

      L80 HEDIT,HEXSCR,HEXKEY,HEXGAP,HEXIO,HEXMENU,HEXSRCH,HEXBLK,HEXKBND,HEXVIRT,HEXHELP,HEDIT/N/E

    The /N flag suppresses the symbol table listing.
    The /E flag specifies the output .COM filename (HEDIT.COM).

    IMPORTANT: After every .MAC file edit, run CPMFMT.PY on the
    modified file(s) before assembling.


    4. MEMORY MAP

      0000h         CP/M warm boot vector
      0005h         BDOS entry point
      005Ch         Default FCB (command line filename)
      0080h         Command tail / DMA buffer
      0100h         TPA start - HEDIT.COM loads here
      ....          Code and data segments (CSEG then DSEG)
      BMDATEND      End of static data (defined in HEXHELP.MAC)
      BMDATEND..    Gap buffer (all remaining TPA memory)
      ..BDOS-1      Top of gap buffer
      BDOS          BDOS handler

    Minimum TPA required: 9 KB (MINMEM = 9*1024)


    5. GAP BUFFER ARCHITECTURE

    HEDIT uses a gap buffer for the edit data.  The buffer occupies
    all free memory from BMDATEND to the top of TPA.

      Memory layout:
        [R1: pre-gap data] [---GAP---] [R2: post-gap data]
        base               GAPBG       GAPEN               base+BSIZE

    The cursor position is always at the gap boundary.  Inserting a
    byte writes it at GAPBG and advances GAPBG.  Deleting removes a
    byte by moving the gap boundary.

    Moving the cursor bulk-copies bytes across the gap:
      - Move right: copy bytes from R2 start to R1 end (forward copy)
      - Move left: copy bytes from R1 end to R2 start (backward copy)

    The gap buffer is purely byte-oriented -- no line delimiters,
    no LF counting.  Navigation is by byte offset:
      - Left/right: +/- 1 byte
      - Up/down: +/- 16 bytes
      - Page: +/- 320 bytes


    6. BUFFER DESCRIPTOR

    Each buffer is described by a 34-byte descriptor (BD_SIZE = 34):

      Offset  Size  Field       Description
      ------  ----  ----------  ----------------------------------
       0      2     BD_BSTAR    Buffer base address in RAM
       2      2     BD_BSIZE    Buffer capacity in bytes
       4      2     BD_GAPBG    Gap start offset (relative to base)
       6      2     BD_GAPEN    Gap end offset (relative to base)
       8      2     BD_TXEND    Logical data length (R1 + R2 size)
      10      2     BD_TOPOFF   Top visible byte offset (aligned to 16)
      12      2     BD_CSOFF    Cursor byte offset
      14      2     BD_MRKBG    Block mark start (FFFFh = unset)
      16      2     BD_MRKEN    Block mark end (FFFFh = unset)
      18      1     BD_MODIF    Modified flag (0 = clean, 1 = dirty)
      19      1     BD_FILEFMT  File format (0 = binary, 1 = Intel HEX)
      20      12    BD_FNAME    Drive (1) + filename (8) + extension (3)
      32      2     BD_BADDR    Base address for Intel HEX files

    CURBDP is a global pointer to the active buffer descriptor.


    7. SCREEN LAYOUT

    The display is organized as follows (80x24 VT100 terminal):

      Row  1: Info bar (filename, size, offset, mode flags)
      Row  2: Column header (dim text)
      Row  3-22: Hex data area (20 rows, 16 bytes each, 320 bytes)
      Row 23: Separator line (80 '=' characters)
      Row 24: Status/message bar

    Data row format (72 visible characters):
      Col  1-4:   Hex address (4 digits, 0000-FFFF)
      Col  5-6:   ": " separator
      Col  7-30:  First 8 hex bytes ("XX XX XX XX XX XX XX XX")
      Col 31:     Group separator space
      Col 32-55:  Second 8 hex bytes ("XX XX XX XX XX XX XX XX")
      Col 56-57:  Gap (2 spaces)
      Col 58-73:  16 ASCII characters (20h-7Eh shown, else '.')

    Color scheme (VT100 SGR codes):
      Address field:  Bold green
      Hex bytes:      Cyan
      ASCII field:    Yellow
      Column header:  Dim
      Separator:      Dim
      Info bar:       Reverse video
      Block marks:    Reverse video


    8. SELECTIVE REDRAW SYSTEM

    The main loop uses a two-level dirty flag system:

      DIRTY    DRTLINE   Action
      -----    -------   ------
        1        *        SCRDRAW: full 20-row redraw + header + separator
        0        1        SCREDCL: current row only
        0        0        No content redraw (cursor-only move)

    INFOBAR and CURPOS always run at MLDONE regardless of flags.

    During block marking (MRKBG set, MRKEN = FFFFh), DIRTY is forced
    to 1 on every main loop iteration so the live highlight preview
    tracks the cursor.

    Block mark highlighting is optimized: per-row highlight boundaries
    (SHHLS, SHHLE) are precomputed by SHHLRNG, and SGR attribute
    changes are emitted only at transition points, not per byte.


    9. KEY INPUT SYSTEM

    HEXKEY.MAC implements a state-machine VT100 key decoder:

      State       Description
      ---------   --------------------------------
      KST_IDL     Idle, no prefix received
      KST_ESC     Received ESC (0x1B)
      KST_CSI     Received ESC [ (CSI sequence)
      KST_SS3     Received ESC O (SS3 sequence)
      KST_CSP     CSI with parameter digits
      KST_CTK     Ctrl-K prefix active
      KST_CTQ     Ctrl-Q prefix active

    GETKEY returns:
      B = key type (KT_NONE, KT_ACT, or KT_CHAR)
      C = action code or character value

    Key dispatch tables:
      KBDTBL   Ctrl codes 0-31 -> action codes (32 bytes)
      CSITBL   CSI sequences: (final_byte, param, action) triples
      SS3TBL   SS3 sequences: (final_byte, action) pairs
      CTKTBL   Ctrl-K prefix: (char, action) pairs
      CTQTBL   Ctrl-Q prefix: (char, action) pairs


    10. FILE I/O

    Binary files:
      Load: read 128-byte records via BF_FREAD, insert each byte via
            GBINSRT, stop at CP/M EOF (1Ah) or read error.
      Save: read logical bytes via GBLOGRD, write 128-byte records
            via BF_FWRITE, pad final record with zeros.

    Intel HEX files:
      Load: auto-detected when first byte is ':' (3Ah).  Parsed
            record by record via IHRDLN/IHPARS.  Base address is
            saved from the first data record (no 0xFF pre-padding).
            Address gaps between records are filled with FFh bytes.
            Type 02/04 extended address records show an error and
            are skipped.
      Save: 16-byte data records with checksums.  Record addresses
            include the base address (BD_BADDR).  Terminated with
            an EOF record (:00000001FF).

    Save creates a .BAK backup by renaming the existing file before
    writing the new version.


    11. SEARCH ENGINE

    HEXSRCH.MAC provides forward search with wrap-around.

    Two search types:
      Hex:   space-separated hex byte pairs ("4D 5A 90 00")
      ASCII: literal text string

    Search algorithm:
      1. Start at CSOFF + 1 (one past cursor)
      2. At each position, try matching SRCHBUF[0..SRCHLEN-1]
         against logical data via GBLOGRD
      3. If end of data reached, wrap to offset 0
      4. Stop when match found or full circle completed

    Maximum search pattern: 64 bytes (SRCHMAX).


    12. BLOCK OPERATIONS

    Block marks use BD_MRKBG and BD_MRKEN in the buffer descriptor.
    Both are FFFFh when no mark is active.

    Mark state machine:
      Both FFFFh          -> Set MRKBG = cursor, MRKEN = FFFFh
      MRKBG set, MRKEN=FF -> Set MRKEN = cursor (swap if needed)
      Both set            -> Clear both to FFFFh

    Copy: reads bytes MRKBG through MRKEN (inclusive) into CLPBUF
          via GBLOGRD.  Maximum clipboard size: 2048 bytes (CLIPMAX).

    Delete: moves cursor to MRKBG, calls GBDELRT for
            (MRKEN - MRKBG + 1) bytes.

    Paste: inserts CLPLEN bytes from CLPBUF at cursor via GBINSRT.


    13. CODING CONVENTIONS

    - Intel 8080 assembly ONLY.  No Z80 instructions (no EX, DJNZ,
      JR, IX/IY, etc.)
    - BDOS calls clobber ALL registers.  Any value needed across a
      CALL BDOS must be saved to memory or stack.
    - M80 truncates symbols to 6 characters.  Avoid symbols that
      differ only after the 6th character.
    - After every .MAC file edit, run: python CPMFMT.PY <file>
    - CSEG for code and read-only data; DSEG for mutable variables.


    14. DEPENDENCIES BETWEEN MODULES

    HEDIT.MAC     imports from all other modules
    HEXSCR.MAC    imports CURBDP, DIRTY, INSMODE, EDITMODE, NIBBLE,
                  GBRDBLK, GBTXEND, GBCSOFF
    HEXKEY.MAC    standalone (no imports except HEDIT.INC constants)
    HEXGAP.MAC    imports CURBDP
    HEXIO.MAC     imports CURBDP, ISLOAD, GBINIT, GBINSRT, GBMVTP,
                  GBTXEND, GBBASE, GBBSIZ, GBGAPBG, GBGAPEN, GBLOGRD,
                  STATMSG, OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO, INFOBAR
    HEXMENU.MAC   imports GETKEY, CURBDP, DIRTY, INSMODE, EDITMODE,
                  FIOPEN, FISAVE, FIPROMPT, FISAVFN, FISMOD, STATMSG,
                  OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO, INFOBAR, SCRDRAW,
                  GBMVTO, GBTXEND, GBCSOFF, SRFIND, HLPSHOW, DOEXIT
    HEXSRCH.MAC   imports CURBDP, DIRTY, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND, GBCSOFF,
                  GBMVTO, STATMSG, STATCLR, OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO
    HEXBLK.MAC    imports CURBDP, DIRTY, GBINSRT, GBDLFT, GBDELRT,
                  GBMVTO, GBCSOFF, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND, STATMSG
    HEXKBND.MAC   imports KBDTBL, CSITBL, SS3TBL, CTKTBL, CTQTBL,
                  STATMSG, OUTSTR
    HEXVIRT.MAC   imports CURBDP, DIRTY, GBINIT, GBMVTP, GBBASE,
                  GBBSIZ, GBGAPEN, GBCSOFF, GBLOGRD, GBTXEND,
                  SCRDRAW, INFOBAR, CURPOS, STATMSG, WRKFCB
    HEXHELP.MAC   imports OUTSTR, OUTCHAR, CURGOTO, DIRTY

